answers.body_markdown:
This relies on the difference between `@MockBean` and `@Autowired`.

`@Autowired`
------------

only does a lookup in the `SpringContext` for a bean of that type. This means that you will need to create that bean if you need to &#39;autowire&#39; it

`@MockBean`
-----------

does exactly what you expect from the name, it creates a &#39;mock&#39; of the service, and injects it as a bean.

so this
```java
class MyTest {
   @MockBean
   MyService myService;
}
```
 is equivalent to this

```java
@Import(MyTest.Config.class)
class MyTest {

   @Autowired
   MyService myService;

   @TestConfiguration
   static class Config {

      @Bean
      MyService myService() {
         return Mockito.mock(MyService.class);
      }
   }
}
```


----------


So, if you need to have a different bean of the `MyService` type in other tests, you need to create the bean in a `@TestConfiguration` annotated class
```java
@Import(MyTest.Config.class)
class MyTest {

   @Autowired
   MyService myService;

   @TestConfiguration
   static class Config {

      @Bean
      MyService myService() {
         return new MyServiceImpl();
      }
   }
}
```
Or, in a class annotated with `@Configuration`
```java
@Import(MyConfig.class)
class MyTest {
   @Autowired
   MyService myService;
}

@Configuration
public class MyConfig {
   @Bean
   MyService myService() {
      return new MyServiceImpl();
   }
}
```

The best solution is to change `@MockBean` to [@SpyBean][1]. And in the method you will be able to do like this:
&gt; kotlin

```kotlin
    @SpyBean
    lateinit var serviceMock: Service

    @Test
    fun smallTest()
        `when`(serviceMock.doSomething())
            .thenReturn(false)

        // your test logic
    }

```


  [1]: https://www.mo4tech.com/springboot-unit-test-spybean-vs-mockbean.html

